ic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: RE: Epic MQ</span><hr size=1> Not knock'n you Uron, sorry if the wording seemed that way. <br><br>It's just the general attitude over all, as I can see and understand a LOT of people saying &quot;no way&quot; to 150k for the rogue epic, yet see a lot of people dumping that much into a green scale and not thinking twice about it being a fair price.  <br><br>It's all about rarety and difficultly in getting the piece when compaired to how &quot;good&quot; the actual item is that I'm knocking.<br><br>&quot;few&quot; people would spend that kind of cash on the rogue epic because of it's &quot;ease&quot;, compaired to what people are forced to do to get the increadibly tough epics like the warrior and mage ones (with the warrior's epic going overboard on the unfairness since it's replacable so soon).  I mean, why pay 150k when you can just go get it right?  And it will last you a good chunk of your characters lifetime.  While other epics are almost impossible to get if you combine server competition into the mix, but will be replaced soon after.  You have to pay the money in that case, because you can't &quot;just go get it&quot;.<br><br>They don't balance out.  If something takes forever to complete it shouldn't be worthless shortly after.  If something takes you a few days to do, you're rewarded with something lasts you a lifetime.<br><br>What they should do, is take the green scale requirement out of the warrior quest altogether.  They should take Quillamaine out of the mage quest altogether.  Would bring them &quot;more&quot; in line with the other epics then (well, mage one anyway.  Their reward lasts them a lifetime as well.  Warrior epic would still be screwed by the fact that they're highly replacable... but at least it would be &quot;obtainable&quot;. without the giant pocket book requirement that hardly any warrior has. finally). <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr 